WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.740
Welcome back. In the last lesson, we decoded
the first five seller questions.

2
00:00:05.420 --> 00:00:09.940
Now we'll finish the set with questions six
through ten, then tie the whole thing back

3
00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:12.060
to how you sound on a real call.

4
00:00:13.240 --> 00:00:14.700
Do I need to make any repairs?

5
00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:21.360
This is huge for a lot of sellers, especially
ones who know their house is in rough

6
00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:24.840
shape. Tell them no. Zero repairs.

7
00:00:25.300 --> 00:00:27.400
We buy properties in any condition.

8
00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:28.860
That's the whole point.

9
00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:32.440
They can leave the place exactly as it is.

10
00:00:33.340 --> 00:00:35.200
Are there any fees or commissions?

11
00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:39.200
They want to know what the real number is.

12
00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:41.619
Are you going to hit them with something
later?

13
00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:48.460
The answer is no. No fees, no commissions,
no closing costs on their end.

14
00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:52.500
The offer number is what they walk away with
at closing, period.

15
00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:55.480
What happens after I sign?

16
00:00:57.460 --> 00:00:59.080
They're nervous about the unknown.

17
00:00:59.740 --> 00:01:03.400
What happens between saying yes and actually
getting a check?

18
00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:08.480
Walk them through it. The transaction team
handles everything from there.

19
00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:12.340
Title work, any inspections, closing
logistics.

20
00:01:13.016 --> 00:01:15.064
They'll know what's happening at each step.

21
00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:20.460
On closing day, they sign the final paperwork
and get their money, usually the same day

22
00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:21.400
or the day after.

23
00:01:22.795 --> 00:01:24.605
Can I stay in the house after selling?

24
00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:29.840
Some sellers need the cash but aren't ready
to move immediately.

25
00:01:30.543 --> 00:01:32.496
Tell them it's something you can discuss.

26
00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:37.480
It's called a leaseback where they'd stay in
the home for a set period after closing,

27
00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:39.580
usually for a small monthly amount.

28
00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:42.560
The acquisition team works out the
specifics.

29
00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:44.760
You're just confirming it's possible.

30
00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:47.340
What if I change my mind?

31
00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:51.300
They're scared of being locked in.

32
00:01:51.800 --> 00:01:56.720
Tell them the contract has an inspection period
built in, which gives both sides time to

33
00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:01.540
review everything. Nothing is final until
both parties are comfortable, and you'd never

34
00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:05.500
want them to move forward unless they feel
genuinely good about it.

35
00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:07.900
Reduce the fear of saying yes.

36
00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:13.180
The thing that ties all of these together is
that you're not performing.

37
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:15.380
You're not delivering lines.

38
00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:20.660
You're talking to another person who needs
information to make a big decision, and

39
00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:24.540
you're giving them that information clearly
and honestly.

40
00:02:24.540 --> 00:02:28.920
If you can do that while sounding like a
real human being and not a recorded message,

41
00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:31.600
you'll handle any question that comes your
way.

42
00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:36.160
Practice saying these answers out loud until
they feel natural.

43
00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:38.260
Say them to yourself in the car.

44
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:42.360
Say them to your dog. Say them in the mirror
if you have to.

45
00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:47.600
The point is that when a seller asks one of
these questions on a live call, you don't

46
00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:52.220
hesitate. You just answer, the way you'd
explain it to a friend who asked.

47
00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:59.600
Alright, next up, the follow-up game where
most of the money actually gets made.
